    "cross_module_architecture": {
      "evidence": [
        "`goseg/protocol/contracts/conformance/fixtures_test.go` imports `groundseg/uploadsvc` and validates upload parser behavior from inside the contracts package test suite, creating a reverse dependency from contract-governance tests to one concrete consumer module.",
        "`README.md` defines one combined backend gate (`go test ./protocol/contracts/... ./uploadsvc/...`) with protocol/contracts maintainers as owner, while enforcement logic is split across contract tests and uploadsvc tests, indicating blurred ownership boundaries rather than a single governance boundary.",
        "`goseg/protocol/actionids/actionids.go`, `goseg/protocol/contracts/familycatalog/catalog.go`, and `goseg/protocol/contracts/family_specs_test.go` each carry overlapping action-contract declarations/strings, with test literals duplicated instead of deriving from one manifest."
      ],
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "confidence": "high"
    }
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "cross_module_architecture",
      "identifier": "contract_tests_reverse_dependency_on_uploadsvc",
      "summary": "Contract-governance tests depend directly on `uploadsvc`, inverting the intended boundary where contracts should be consumer-agnostic.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/protocol/contracts/conformance/fixtures_test.go",
        "goseg/uploadsvc/actions_test.go",
        "README.md"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`TestUploadParserActionsMatchConformanceBindings` in `fixtures_test.go` imports and calls `uploadsvc.SupportedUploadActions`, `uploadsvc.UploadActionContractByAction`, and `uploadsvc.ParseUploadAction`.",
        "This places consumer behavior assertions inside the contracts package test layer rather than in consumer-owned conformance tests.",
        "README backend gate ownership is assigned to protocol/contracts maintainers while also requiring `./uploadsvc/...`, reinforcing cross-module ownership coupling."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Move consumer conformance assertions into `uploadsvc` (or a dedicated integration-conformance package) and expose a small neutral contract fixture/assertion API from `protocol/contracts` so dependency direction remains contracts -> consumers (not consumers pulled into contract package tests).",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "root_cause_cluster": "contract_governance_boundary_blur"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "cross_module_architecture",
      "identifier": "contract_source_of_truth_fragmented",
      "summary": "Action contract governance is fragmented across multiple files with duplicated literals, increasing drift risk between docs, catalog, and tests.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/protocol/actionids/actionids.go",
        "goseg/protocol/contracts/familycatalog/catalog.go",
        "goseg/protocol/contracts/family_specs_test.go",
        "README.md"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`actionids.go` defines namespace/action/contract IDs; `catalog.go` defines names/descriptions/owners; `family_specs_test.go` redefines descriptor strings in test specs (`\"upload open endpoint\"`, `\"open upload endpoint contract\"`, `\"upload open endpoint message\"`).",
        "The README quality-gate language references family-governance tests but there is no single declared manifest in these files that all tests and docs consume.",
        "Manual duplication across IDs, descriptors, and test fixtures creates multi-point updates for one contract change."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Create one canonical contract manifest (ID, namespace/action, descriptor, governance metadata) and generate/derive action IDs, family catalog specs, and conformance fixtures from it; update tests to assert against generated/canonical data rather than inline literals.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "codebase",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "root_cause_cluster": "contract_governance_boundary_blur"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "cross_module_architecture",
      "identifier": "owner_boundary_is_stringly_typed",
      "summary": "Governance ownership uses unconstrained string values, so module-boundary contracts are not structurally enforced.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/protocol/contracts/familycatalog/catalog.go",
        "goseg/protocol/contracts/family_specs_test.go",
        "README.md"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`catalog.go` sets `Owner` as raw strings (`\"system/wifi\"`, `\"uploadsvc\"`, `\"startram\"`) with no typed domain or compile-time registry in these reviewed files.",
        "`family_specs_test.go` similarly uses free-form `OwnerModule: \"uploadsvc\"` in governance metadata fixtures.",
        "README assigns owner responsibility for the contract gate, but the owner identity model in code is not normalized or validated against a maintained module registry."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Introduce a typed owner/module identifier registry (constants or enum-like type) and validate all governance specs against it during contract-family validation so ownership and boundary declarations cannot silently drift.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "contract_governance_boundary_blur"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "Contract governance is distributed across docs, tests, and catalogs without one authoritative machine-checked manifest.",
      "Conformance responsibilities are split across package boundaries, causing ownership and dependency-direction ambiguity."
    ],
